Helm in Kubernetes
Helm is the package manager for Kubernetes — it simplifies deploying and managing applications on a cluster.


Core Concepts
Chart — A Helm package containing all Kubernetes resource definitions (Deployments, Services, ConfigMaps, etc.) needed to run an application.
Release — A running instance of a chart deployed to a cluster. You can deploy the same chart multiple times as separate releases.
Repository — A place where charts are stored and shared (like Docker Hub, but for Helm charts).
Values — Configuration inputs that customize a chart's templates at deploy time.



How It Works


Chart (templates + values.yaml)
        ↓
   helm install / upgrade
        ↓
  Rendered Manifests
        ↓
  Kubernetes API → Resources created


Chart Structure


my-chart/
├── Chart.yaml          # Chart metadata (name, version, description)
├── values.yaml         # Default configuration values
├── templates/          # Kubernetes manifest templates
│   ├── deployment.yaml
│   ├── service.yaml
│   ├── ingress.yaml
│   └── _helpers.tpl    # Reusable template snippets
└── charts/             # Sub-chart dependencies


The Chart.yaml file is the metadata manifest for a Helm chart. Every chart must have one.

Minimal Example

Chart.yaml

apiVersion: v2
name: my-app
version: 1.0.0


values.yaml

replicaCount: 2

image:
  repository: nginx
  tag: "1.25"

service:
  type: ClusterIP
  port: 80

ingress:
  enabled: true
  host: myapp.example.com


templates/deployment.yaml


apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: {{ .Release.Name }}-app
spec:
  replicas: {{ .Values.replicaCount }}
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: {{ .Release.Name }}
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: {{ .Release.Name }}
    spec:
      containers:
        - name: app
          image: "{{ .Values.image.repository }}:{{ .Values.image.tag }}"
          ports:
            - containerPort: 80


templates/service.yaml


apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: {{ .Release.Name }}-svc
spec:
  type: {{ .Values.service.type }}
  selector:
    app: {{ .Release.Name }}
  ports:
    - port: {{ .Values.service.port }}
      targetPort: 80



templates/ingress.yaml


{{- if .Values.ingress.enabled }}
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: Ingress
metadata:
  name: {{ .Release.Name }}-ingress
spec:
  rules:
    - host: {{ .Values.ingress.host }}
      http:
        paths:
          - path: /
            pathType: Prefix
            backend:
              service:
                name: {{ .Release.Name }}-svc
                port:
                  number: {{ .Values.service.port }}
{{- end }}


Install it

Yes! my-release is just a name you choose — call it anything.

helm install my-release ./my-chart

# Override a value
helm install my-release ./my-chart --set replicaCount=3

# Disable ingress
helm install my-release ./my-chart --set ingress.enabled=false


How they connect

values.yaml
    │
    ├──▶ deployment.yaml  (replicaCount, image)
    ├──▶ service.yaml     (service.type, service.port)
    └──▶ ingress.yaml     (ingress.enabled, ingress.host)


Verify everything is running

# See the release
helm list

# Check pods
kubectl get pods

# Check service
kubectl get svc

# Check ingress
kubectl get ingress


Later — upgrade, rollback, uninstall


# Change replicas to 5
helm upgrade my-release ./my-chart --set replicaCount=5

# Oops, rollback
helm rollback my-release 1

# Done with it
helm uninstall my-release

You can even install the same chart multiple times with different names:

helm install dev-app    ./my-chart --set image.tag="1.24"
helm install staging-app ./my-chart --set image.tag="1.25"
helm install prod-app   ./my-chart --set image.tag="1.26"

Helm vs kubectl difference (commonly asked)

kubectl → applies raw YAML one by one
Helm    → manages as a single package with versioning

helm dry-run (interviewers love this)

# See what will be deployed without actually deploying
helm install my-release ./my-chart --dry-run --debug

Helm Repo commands

helm repo add bitnami https://charts.bitnami.com/bitnami
helm repo update
helm search repo nginx
helm pull bitnami/nginx

Likely Interview Questions & Quick Answers:
Q: What is a Helm chart?

Package containing all K8s manifests + templates + default values to deploy an app

Q: Difference between Chart and Release?

Chart is the package, Release is a deployed instance of that chart

Q: Can you deploy same chart twice?

Yes, with different release names — dev-app, staging-app, prod-app

Q: How do you rollback in Helm?

helm rollback <release-name> <revision-number>

Q: Where are default values stored?

values.yaml — can be overridden via --set or -f custom-values.yaml

Q: Difference between helm install and helm upgrade?

install → first time deploy, upgrade → update existing release
